<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Old world rotation mobs? Two helpings please. Hard to beat mobs that have quests to get around em? One helping please, because it takes too long to do it by quests and we can’t beat it on our own.<br>
<br>
The double standard being an alliance at whim, and of taking two shares of loot off rotation mobs, while needing to team mobs that drop even better loot, but insisting its just “flag progression”, and its all ok because “Hey, there’s a quest”.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->Lets look for a single second what it would mean ...seriously... to rotate Aerin'Dar (a rotation to preserve order and provide scheduling) while exempting that rotation from the 'no team' rule.  What does that really mean?  It means that 2 guilds of 30-40 people can team up as an alliance (as one entity) for that one mob rotation, while your 1 guild of 72 people can be placed on the same rotation ...essentially now getting twice the amount of BETTER LOOT, by your own admission, because there is only one of you and two of them.  They have to either divide the loot equally among the two, or alternate loot on each cycle.  Either way, each guild in that alliance is getting half of what your one guild is getting.  THAT is the price they pay to be an alliance on that one particular mob.<br>
<br>
So, in the big picture, yes ..they are doubling up on one mob (getting half the loot from that mob ...loot that you say is BETTER than loot from mobs currently on rotation) and still maintaining their individual guild rotations in the old world (1 to 1 ratio compared to you on loot that you say is CRAP compared to what can be found in PoP).  Comparing them any other way is wrong ...in this case, you can't look at the 'big' picture and extrapolate comparisons from it.  That's like saying there should be two attempts per rotation cycle on Mob #1 because his loot is about half as equivalent than Mob #2 who you only get 1 attempt at each cycle.<br>
