<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp Congratulations on Sontalak.  And I hate to have to say this, but in threads like this it seems I must, but seriously, Congratulations.  Sont’s a bitz of a dragon, and something to be proud of stomping on your own like that.<br>
<br>
<br>
Rigorre,<br>
<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp I particularly enjoy your method of quoting half-sentences and removing all context.  People may groan about the length of my posts, but at least I keep the context of what I quote.<br>
<br>
I don’t enjoy you putting words in my mouth:<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr> So, in the big picture, yes ..they are doubling up on one mob (getting half the loot from that mob ...loot that you say is BETTER than loot from mobs currently on rotation)<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
I have said, several times, that the loot is as good as VT/Ssra gear, and for guilds not on those rotations to claim Aerin Dar A) doesn’t drop items, or B) those items are subpar, is completely inaccurate.  I’ve already gone out on a limb, and with a fair amount of confidence of being right, that regardless of what items dropped from Aerin Dar that day to CB/VOLS, those two items are among the best those two guilds have seen.  Quite simply, dismissing the quality of his loot as non-existent or subpar is not being accurate.<br>
<br>
Your idea of those mobs being on rotation AND allowing teaming is a step back not forward.  You fail to account for the fact that yes, while they “suffer” by only getting one item each from a mob they normally couldn’t touch on their own, they are getting double the loot every other guild gets on *every* rotation mob they are currently on.  Let’s look at that again, in case you missed it – net gain: 1 item each they can’t get on their own, and one full complete set of loot from all other rotations they are on.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr> And, once again, you are on the wrong track. Having it handed on a 'silver platter' implies that you will get the flag using your resources and your l33t skills ... and hand it over to me. No one is suggesting you do anything of the kind.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
No, you are demanding my restraint, and I agree it makes sense to show that restraint, but within reason.  I don’t permakill Behemoth so that other guilds can get access to content that isn’t fomally rotated, but because of that restraint, other guilds take advantage of its status of being “up” as a sign no one is interested in it.  <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr> Who told you it wasn't?!<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
So which of this week’s brand new players did you personally set out to make sure they had their input reflected on what goes on here?  Your “registering to vote” if you will.  Since not every player on the Rathe has input on what goes on here, and I mean, *every* player (that guy you watched walk out of the store and who logged onto the Rathe yesterday, yah, him too), that makes it not a representative democracy of the Rathe.  So be careful which way you wave that elitist paintbrush, because we have all agreed to this system for the last three years, and where exactly you fall in that is only determined by what mobs you’ve killed, unassisted.  Haven’t killed Rallos Zek?  Guess what, you don’t get to say one meaningful word about what goes on in running it.  Want input?  Kill him and get on it, then see if you can convince the others that your idea is better.  It’s not a perfect system, but it sure is better than what people on other servers have to put up with.  <br>
<br>
The rotation system was setup to organize sharing between guilds that could kill certain content.  It makes no sense to share with someone who can’t kill said content.  Think I’m the only one who realizes this?  Last time you killed DesireableBigMob X, did you ask the other 3 people in the zone if they wanted to take their fair shot at the mob?  If you didn’t, why not?  Aren’t we all about sharing and complete altruism?  Isn’t that the high horse your riding on?  <br>
<br>
So to answer your question, yes, those guilds who killed it first get to set the precedents on the server – that is how this game has evolved on all levels.  Where and how do you think various zone conventions came from?  Why are the Arch Magi and Ghoul Lord separate camps on our server?  Why does the Frenzied Ghoul get the Sentinel as well?  From the first people into the zone making up common sense, fair rules that make sense.  Trying to claim King and Lord at the same time is impractical (back when the level cap was L 50 and King was a 2 group camp).  If you look beyond your own drive for “new phat xp zones”, you’d see that these are fair rules we’ve played by for the last three years.  Inflating your numbers for one encounter, while rotating other content as separate entities just isn’t fair to the rest of the people who remain separate entities for all content and play within the means their guild’s abilities and skills can provide for them.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr> Constitution of the RTA<br>
RTA Rotation Rules<br>
<br>
and<br>
<br>
Everquest Rules of Conduct<br>
==============<br>
Bill of rights<br>
<br>
Everquest EULA<br>
<br>
*It's not possible to find a Bill of rights specific towards the RTA because, surprisingly, anyone below Teir III doesn't apparently have any rights.*<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Who made those RTA rotation rules you list as the Constitution?  Were you even playing?  If you were, was it in a capacity that had anything to do with the high end game on the Rathe?  If you weren’t, you honestly think it was our responsibility to go to each of 5-10,000 players who log on at various times of day playing from all around the world and make sure to ask each and every one what their vote was on matters that they had absolutely no understanding of?  No, it wasn’t, and in such a free form society as EQ is, that is not how you make order out of chaos.  You create a system that the strong will buy into, or else the system won’t work.  Fortunately, our system dealt with how people would later be added to the “exclusivity” of the rotations, so that it had buy in from the smaller guilds knowing that diligence and effort would pay off and if they followed the rules and conventions of the system, that it would pay off.  It’s a delicate balance, but make no bones about it, it’s not a democracy based on making sure everyone gets unlimited guaranteed chances at whatever content they might desire, nor on people giving input into rotations they aren’t participants on.  I’m not going out of my way to wait on United Necros to get enough keys to kill Emp before I kill him again, nor is FK nor is SoTE.  When they get the keys, and can kill Blood, then they can take their shot, having shown they at least understand what is required to win.  Once they are on rotation, they can give ideas on how to better run the rotation, but as its fairly simple and very effective at sharing content between those who can kill, it’s hard to improve on.<br>
<br>
As for you referencing the EULA and PnP policies, be careful, there is a LOT of leeway on what can be done there that doesn’t violate those.  And even violating those, doesn’t seem to carry as harsh a sentence as you might hope (sadly).<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
Tammasoul,<br>
